''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'',<ref name=\"CNNBio\" /><ref name=\"Bio\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cnncommentary.com/2018/04/12/chris-cuomo-returns-to-primetime-june-4/ |title=Chris Cuomo returns to primetime June 4 |date=April 12, 2018 |website=CNN Commentary.com |access-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> and before his current show'','' he was one of two co-anchors of the weekday edition of ''[[New Day (TV program)|New Day]]'', a three-hour morning news show, until May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/24/us/chris-cuomo-goodbye-new-day-prime-time-cnntv/index.html |title=A tearful good-bye as Chris Cuomo leaves 'New Day' for 'Prime Time' |last=Ellefson |first=Lindsey |date=May 24, 2018 |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCuomo was born in the New York City borough of [[Queens, New York|Queens]]. He is the youngest child of [[Mario Cuomo]], the former [[Governor of New York]], and [[Matilda Cuomo]] (n\u00e9e Raffa), and the brother of [[Andrew Cuomo]], the current Governor of New York.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> His parents were both of [[Italian-American|Italian]] descent; his paternal grandparents were from [[Nocera Inferiore]] and [[Tramonti, Campania|Tramonti]] in the [[Campania]] region of southern Italy, while his maternal grandparents were from [[Sicily]] (his grandfather from [[Messina]]).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\">{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Blauner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--cCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|title=All Star Family Feud: The Governor's In-Laws Battle Over a Father's Legacy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=February 13, 1989|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Newsday10201988>{{cite news| first =Michael| last =Arena | author2 =Marianne Arneberg |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/104068528.html?dids=104068528:104068528&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+20%2C+1988&author=By+Michael+Arena+and+Marianne+Arneberg&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=Cuomo's+Father-in-Law+Dies&pqatl=google|title=Cuomo's Father-in-Law Dies|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 20, 1988|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCuomo was educated at [[The Albany Academy]], a private university preparatory day school in [[Albany, New York]], followed by [[Yale University|Yale]], where he obtained an undergraduate degree, and [[Fordham University|Fordham]], where he obtained his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) in 1995. He is a licensed attorney.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref>[https://www.biography.com/media-figure/chris-cuomo \"Chris Cuomo Biography\"], ''biography.com'', Retrieved August 5, 2019</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCuomo's early career in journalism included appearances related to social and political issues on [[CNBC]], [[MSNBC]], and [[CNN]]. He was a correspondent for [[Fox News]] and Fox Broadcast Network's ''Fox Files'', where he covered a wide range of stories focusing on controversial social issues.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\">[https://abcnews.go.com/2020/ChrisCuomo/chris-cuomos-biography/story?id=3147482&singlePage=true \"Chris Cuomo's biography\"]. ABC News. 2014, Retrieved February 1, 2014.</ref> He also served as a political policy analyst for Fox News.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nAt ABC and as co-anchor of ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', his coverage included a look at heroin addiction.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> His year-long coverage revealed the heroin addiction affecting suburban families.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> His other work has included coverage of the Haiti earthquake, child custody, bullying, and homeless teens. Policy change has come after his undercover look at for-profit school recruiters, leading to an industry cleanup; and Cuomo's tip from a BMW owner led to a recall of over 150,000 affected models.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\nFrom September 2006 to December 2009, he was the news anchor for ''[[Good Morning America]]''.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> He was the primary reporter on breaking news stories, both in the U.S. and around the world, including dozens of assignments in some 10 countries.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> He covered the war on terrorism, embedded on multiple occasions in Pakistan, Afghanistan, and Iraq<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/> (where his convoy was hit by an IED).<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> In the U.S., he covered shootings such as [[Virginia Tech shooting|Virginia Tech]], [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood]], and the Pennsylvania Amish school shootings, Hurricanes Katrina and Rita, the Sago Mine collapse, and the Minneapolis bridge collapse in August 2007.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> He anchored morning and evening coverage.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\nHe has a website, \"Cuomo on the Case,\" where he takes questions, and which acts as a platform for his reporting and discussion on a number of issues.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> He had two weekly digital programs on [[ABC News]], ''The Real Deal'' and ''Focus on Faith'', that discussed matters of spirituality.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/> He also appeared with Father Edward Beck on ''[[ABC News Now]]'', the network's 24-hour digital outlet.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\nIn February 2013, Cuomo moved to [[CNN]] to co-host its morning show.<ref name=\"CNNBio\" /><ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|title=Chris Cuomo: I'm moving to CNN!|url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/01/28/chris-cuomo-cnn-erin-burnett-abc-good-morning-america/|publisher=TMZ: EHM Productions, Inc.|date=January 29, 2013|accessdate=February 1, 2014}}</ref> He made his debut on CNN as field anchor on the February 8, 2013, episode of ''[[Piers Morgan Tonight]]'', covering the [[February 2013 nor'easter]].<ref>[http://piersmorgan.blogs.cnn.com/2013/02/08/chris-cuomo-debuts-on-cnn-field-anchors-amidst-blizzard-its-truly-an-honor-to-join-the-cnn-team-thank-you-for-the-coat/ Chris Cuomo debuts on CNN, field anchors amidst blizzard: \"It's truly an honor to join the CNN team\"], ''CNN'', Atlanta, GA: Cable News Network/Turner Broadcasting System, Inc., February 8, 2013, Retrieved February 1, 2014.</ref> In March 2018, while serving as the co-anchor of CNN's morning show ''[[New Day (TV series)|New Day]],'' it was announced that Cuomo would move to primetime to host ''Cuomo Primetime''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grynbaum|first1=Michael|title=CNN Moves Chris Cuomo to Prime Time|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/business/media/chris-cuomo-cnn.html|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=March 14, 2018|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, sister network [[HLN (TV network)|HLN]] premiered a new documentary series hosted by the anchor, ''[[Inside with Chris Cuomo]]'', which focuses on \"stories affecting real people, in real towns and cities across America.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/chris-cuomo-anchors-inside-hln-fridays-cnn-1202189857/|title=Chris Cuomo Anchors 'Inside' For HLN Over Five Fridays|last=Moraes|first=Lisa de|date=October 17, 2017|work=Deadline|access-date=October 21, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, he began hosting a two-hour weekday radio show \"Let\u2019s Get After It\" on the [[P.O.T.U.S. (Sirius XM)|P.O.T.U.S.]] channel on [[SiriusXM]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.siriusxm.com/cnns-chris-cuomo-to-host-live-weekday-show-exclusively-for-siriusxm/|title=CNN's Chris Cuomo to host live weekday show exclusively for SiriusXM|date=September 19, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCuomo has received multiple [[Emmy Award]] nominations. His ''[[Good Morning America]]'' profile of the 12-year-old poet [[Mattie Stepanek]] was recognized with a News Emmy, making Cuomo one of the youngest correspondents to receive a News Emmy in network news history.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\nHe has been awarded Polk and [[Peabody Award]]s for team coverage. His work has been recognized in the areas of breaking news, business news, and legal news, with the [[RTNDA Edward R. Murrow Award|Edward R. Murrow Award]] for breaking news coverage, the 2005 [[Gerald Loeb Award]] for Television Deadline business reporting for \"Money for Nothing?\",<ref name=LOEB-2005>{{cite web|url=http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/x8826.xml |title=2005 Winners|website=[[UCLA Anderson School of Management]]|accessdate=May 22, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051216115915/http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/x8826.xml|archive-date=December 16, 2005|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> and the American Bar Association Silver Gavel Award for investigating juvenile justice.<ref name=\"CNNBio\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2001, Cuomo married ''[[Gotham (magazine)|Gotham]]'' magazine editor Cristina Greeven<ref name=\"Bio\" /> in a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] ceremony in [[Southampton, New York]].<ref name=\"Wedding\">Tuma, Debbie; Becker, Maki (November 25, 2001). [http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/mario-youngest-son-weds-article-1.926225 Mario's youngest son weds]. ''New York Daily News''. New York, NY: New York Daily News.</ref> They reside in [[Manhattan]] with their three children.<ref name=\"CNNBio\" /><ref name=\"Bio\" /><ref name=\"ABC\" /><ref name=\"Child\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/02/03/chris-cuomo-cristina-gree_n_447403.html|title=Chris Cuomo, Cristina Greeven Cuomo Welcome Baby Girl Carolina |last=Shea|first=Danny|date=April 5, 2010|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=February 4, 2011}}</ref> Cuomo also owns a home in Southampton.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/19/nyregion/cuomo-drawn-to-hamptons-by-family-not-social-scene.html|title=Cuomo Drawn to Hamptons by Family, Not Social Scene|first=Thomas|last=Kaplan|date=July 18, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=February 23, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 2019, in [[Shelter Island, New York]], Cuomo threatened to throw a heckler down a flight of stairs at a bar, and chastised him with profanity-laced insults after the man called him [[Fredo Corleone|Fredo]], in reference to the fictional character from ''[[The Godfather (novel)|The Godfather]]'' novel and [[The Godfather (film series)|films]]. Cuomo told the man that the use of the name \"Fredo\" was tantamount to \"the [[nigger|n-word]]\" for Italian-Americans,<ref>{{cite news |last=Gold |first=Michael |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/13/nyregion/fredo-cuomo-video.html |title=CNN's Chris Cuomo Threatens Man Who Called Him 'Fredo' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814014636/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/13/nyregion/fredo-cuomo-video.html |archivedate=August 14, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> which caused debate on [[Twitter]] about the claimed equivalency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/08/13/chris-cuomo-fredo-video-sparks-debate-fredo-ethnic-slur/1995997001/|title=Chris Cuomo said 'Fredo' is an ethnic slur as he erupted in anger in a viral video. Is it?|publisher=usatoday.com|date=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/08/13/how-fredo-tragic-godfather-character-became-an-insult-wielded-by-trump/|title=How Fredo, the tragic 'Godfather' character, became an insult wielded by Trump|last=Horton|first=Alex|date=August 13, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=August 15, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814003848/https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/08/13/how-fredo-tragic-godfather-character-became-an-insult-wielded-by-trump/|archivedate=August 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2019/08/chris-cuomo-fredo-not-an-ethnic-slur/|title='Fredo' Is Not an Ethnic Slur|last=Nardi|first=William Z.|date=August 14, 2019|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref> Cuomo addressed the incident publicly, tweeting his appreciation to his supporters but acknowledging that he \"should be better than what [he] oppose[s].\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Rupar |first=Aaron |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/8/13/20803708/chris-cuomo-fredo-video-explained |title=The viral video of Chris Cuomo going berserk over being called \"Fredo,\" explained |work=[[Vox Media]] |date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814004347/https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/8/13/20803708/chris-cuomo-fredo-video-explained |archivedate=August 14, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAmid the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Cuomo announced on March 31 that he had been diagnosed with [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/media/chris-cuomo-coronavirus/index.html|title=CNN anchor Chris Cuomo diagnosed with coronavirus; he will continue working from home|publisher=[[CNN]]|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=March 31, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2020/03/31/chris-cuomo-tests-positive-coronavirus-covid-19/5094751002/|title=COVID-19 positive, Chris Cuomo talks about chest 'tightness;' Don Lemon tears up for friend|website=[[USA Today]]|last1=Reed|first1=Anika|last2=Truitt|first2=Brian|date=March 31, 2020|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Since then, he has broadcast his usual weekday program from his home, where he is quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[Politico]]|url=https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2020/04/06/chris-cuomo-stay-in-bed-167297|last=Weiss|first=Joanna|date=April 6, 2020|title=Chris Cuomo, Stay in Bed|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Cuomo later claimed he had a [[hallucination]] of his dead father, former New York Governor Mario Cuomo, as a result of symptoms from the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chris-cuomo-coronavirus-fever-hallucinate-dad-mario/|title=CNN's Chris Cuomo says his coronavirus fever got so bad, he hallucinated seeing his dead father|publisher=cbsnews.com|date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> On April 15, Cuomo announced on his program that his wife, Cristina, tested positive for COVID-19,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/media/2020/04/15/chris-cuomo-wife-diagnosed-coronavirus-governor-andrew-cuomo-sot-cpt-vpx.cnn|title=Chris Cuomo announces wife has virus: It breaks my heart|publisher=cnn.com|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> and on April 22, his wife revealed that their 14-year-old son Mario also tested positive for the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2020/04/22/coronavirus-chris-cuomos-son-mario-has-covid-19-cristina-cuomo-says/3006596001/|title='My heart hurts': Cristina Cuomo reveals 14-year-old son Mario has COVID-19|publisher=usatoday.com|date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cuomo family]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Andrew Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{CNN Anchors|state=collapsed}}\n{{Mario Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{GeraldLoebAward Television}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Chris}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Cuomo family]]\n[[Category:Fordham University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Gerald Loeb Award winners for Television]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:News & Documentary Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:The Albany Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo]]\n", "name_user": "Barefoot through the chollas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Cuomo"}
